ver directly "missionized," the Urapmin began in the 1960s to send young men to study with Baptist missionaries living among neighboring communities. By the late 1970s, the Urapmin had undergone a charismatic revival, abandoning their traditional religion for a Christianity intensely focused on human sinfulness and driven by a constant sense of millennial expectation. Exploring the Christian culture of the Urapmin, Joel Robbins shows how its preoccupations provide keys to understanding the nature of cultural change more generally. In so doing, he offers one of the richest available anthropological accounts of Christianity as a lived religion. Theoretically ambitious and engagingly written, his book opens a unique perspective on a Melanesian society, religious experience, and the very nature of rapid cultural change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianityzPapua New GuineazUrapmin. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  a1960s.  aanthropology.  abaptist missionaries.  achristian converts.  achristian culture.  achristian life.  achristian missionaries.  achristianity.  acultural anthropologists.  acultural change.  acultural perspective.  adiscussion books.  agood and evil.  ahuman condition.  amelanesian society.  amoral torment.  amorality and sin.  anonfiction.  apapua new guinea society.  apapua new guinea.  arapid change.  areligious experiences.  areligious studies.  aremote tribe.  asinfulness.  asocial anthropology.  asocial change.  atheoretical.  aurapmin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023799540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093708640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co